        "For millennia, the high glaciers of Europe, Asia, and the Americas have acted as unlikely custodians of human history. Extreme cold arrests decomposition so thoroughly that organic materials preserved in ice can emerge, centuries later, in near-perfect condition. Scientists and archaeologists have long known that glaciers advance and retreat, but the pace at which they are currently receding has transformed them, in the words of one glaciologist, into \"libraries that are burning faster than we can read them.\"",
        "The implications of this accelerating melt extend well beyond the purely scientific. Mountain communities that have depended on glacial meltwater for irrigation and drinking water are confronting an existential threat to their livelihoods. But for archaeologists, each retreating ice margin also represents a racing clock: once an artefact is exposed to summer temperatures, biological decay resumes with startling speed.",
        "The range of materials that survive glacial entombment is astonishing. Leather, wool, hair, wood, and even foodstuffs have been recovered in states of preservation that conventional burial in soil almost never achieves. The chemistry of ice entombment is straightforward: in sub-zero anaerobic conditions, the bacteria and fungi that ordinarily drive decomposition cannot function.",
        "Not all glacial finds are prehistoric. The Alps have yielded artefacts from every major conflict fought in or near the mountains, including the First and Second World Wars. Soldiers who went missing in high-altitude engagements have been recovered with their equipment, uniforms, and personal effects intact, presenting military historians with primary evidence of a kind rarely available from conventional battlefields.",
        "The logistical challenges of glacial archaeology are considerable. High-altitude sites are difficult to access, weather windows are narrow, and the melt itself may rebury or destroy an object within a single season. Teams working in the Schnalstal glacier in the Italian Alps, for example, routinely employ satellite-guided survey drones to detect anomalies in the ice surface before committing field personnel to dangerous terrain.",
        "Conservation once the objects are removed presents an equally demanding set of problems. The transition from sub-zero, oxygen-free conditions to a temperate laboratory environment must be managed with extraordinary care. Rapid temperature change causes ice crystals within the artefact's cellular structure to expand and rupture, while sudden exposure to atmospheric oxygen triggers oxidative reactions that can disfigure or destroy surfaces within hours.",
        "Funding for this branch of archaeology is chronically precarious. Unlike dramatic excavations in desert sands or tropical jungles, glacial fieldwork rarely yields the photogenic golden treasures that attract public attention and private sponsorship. The work is painstaking, the finds are often fragmentary, and the scientific rewards, though genuine, are seldom immediate.",
        "What emerges from all this effort is a portrait of human life in mountain environments that no written record could supply. Clothing styles, dietary choices, trade routes, and metallurgical techniques that might otherwise be inferred only from ambiguous textual sources become tangible, dateable, and measurable. The glaciers, even as they vanish, are insisting on being heard."
