        "Rent is often the decisive variable. Many long-established secondhand shops occupy premises that were taken on at favourable rates decades ago, and landlords in secondary locations have found that a bookshop generates more goodwill and foot traffic than a vacant unit. The combination of below-market rents and near-zero stock costs produces a cost structure that a new-book retailer could not approach.",
        "The prediction proved spectacularly wrong. Between 2010 and 2020, the number of independent secondhand bookshops in Britain actually increased, a trend mirrored in the United States, France, and the Netherlands. Physical bookshops, it turned out, were not competing with the internet so much as occupying a different emotional register of the reading experience.",
        "Charity shops and house-clearance sales are the primary sources of stock for most dealers, supplemented by customers who bring in boxes of unwanted volumes. The result is an inventory that is perpetually renewed at minimal cost, and the dealer's skill lies not in buying well but in pricing well: recognising which volumes will sell quickly at a premium and which will linger until marked down.",
        "This bifurcation has had tangible consequences for the internal economics of the trade. Volumes that once formed the reliable turnover of a secondhand shop, standard editions of canonical texts, popular fiction from the preceding decade, have been commoditised to the point of worthlessness. Shops that once stocked broadly now curate aggressively, focusing on areas of genuine rarity or local relevance.",
