        "Early theoretical work on the problem was carried out by the mathematician Art Winfree in the 1960s and refined by Steven Strogatz and Rennie Mirollo in a landmark 1990 paper. Their model demonstrated that a population of oscillators with slightly different natural frequencies would, above a critical coupling threshold, spontaneously lock into synchrony, a result that translated directly to the biological case.",
        "The stereo camera data revealed that synchrony does not sweep through the population from a single starting point, as one might expect of a wave emanating from a dominant individual. Instead, multiple local clusters achieve phase-lock independently and then gradually merge, a process the researchers termed \"cluster coalescence,\" which takes approximately twenty minutes on a typical observation night.",
